## 20. Economic Viability & Business Model

### Revenue Streams (MVP)

**Platform fee:** 5% on every completed booking. This is deducted before the provider receives their payment. At ₦5,000 average booking value with 1,000 monthly bookings, this generates ₦250,000/month at early scale.

**Why 5% and not more:** Informal workers in Nigeria are price-sensitive. A 5% fee is low enough to not be the reason someone avoids the platform, but aggregated across thousands of bookings it is meaningful. The actual take-rate can be raised as the platform builds dependency.

### Path to 10,000 Users

**Phase 1 (0–500 users) — City seed:** Launch in one LGA of Lagos. Manually onboard 50 providers across 5 categories. Use social media (Instagram, WhatsApp groups) to drive customer sign-ups. Target: ₦500k in GMV in the first month.

**Phase 2 (500–2,000 users) — City expansion:** Expand to 5 LGAs in Lagos. Introduce referral incentives — providers who refer other providers get a ₦1,000 wallet credit. First month free of platform fees for new providers drives supply-side growth.

**Phase 3 (2,000–10,000 users) — Multi-city:** Port to Abuja and Port Harcourt. API agreements with 2 microfinance institutions to offer Platinum-tier providers small working capital loans. This creates a new revenue stream (origination fees from partner lenders) and a retention incentive (providers stay on the platform to maintain their score).

### Unit Economics at 10,000 Users

Assuming 60% providers (6,000) and 40% customers (4,000), and an average provider completing 3 bookings/month at ₦5,000 each:

- Monthly GMV: 6,000 providers × 3 bookings × ₦5,000 = ₦90,000,000
- Platform revenue (5%): ₦4,500,000/month (~$3,000 USD/month)
- Infrastructure cost: ~$50/month (Supabase Pro + Render + Vercel)
- AI cost (Claude API at ~100 requests/day): ~$30/month

The unit economics are strongly positive well before 10,000 users.

