## 21. Scalability Plan

### From 10,000 to National (1,000,000+ users)

The architecture is designed so that scale is additive, not structural. No rewrites required.

| Layer | MVP | At Scale |
|---|---|---|
| Database | Supabase free tier | Supabase Pro → then dedicated Postgres with read replicas |
| Search | Postgres lat/lng math | Add PostGIS extension (already Postgres-native) → then Elasticsearch |
| Caching | None | Redis for session cache, wallet balance cache, search result cache |
| Background jobs | node-cron in Express process | Extract to dedicated worker process (BullMQ + Redis queue) |
| File storage | Supabase Storage | Supabase Storage scales automatically with CDN |
| AI cost management | All requests real-time | Cache AI search results for identical queries (Redis, 1hr TTL) |
| Backend | Single Render instance | Horizontal scaling via Render or migrate to AWS ECS |
| Monolith → microservices | Modular monolith | Extract Squad/AI/notifications as separate services using existing module boundaries |

### Why the Modular Monolith Enables Scale

Because the backend is structured as independent modules (each with its own routes, controller, service, and integration clients), extracting any module into a separate service requires:
1. Creating a new Express app
2. Moving the module folder into it
3. Replacing direct function calls with HTTP calls or a message queue

No business logic rewrites. This is the key scalability design decision.

